<task id="R3-065" project="spaarke-platform-foundations-r3">
  <metadata>
    <title>Canvas-server mapping drift integration test (CI)</title>
    <status>completed</status>
    <completion-date>2026-06-21</completion-date>
    <completion-notes>
2 new integration tests added at tests/integration/Sprk.Bff.Api.IntegrationTests/Playbooks/
CanvasServerMappingDriftTests.cs (Traits: Category=Integration, Phase=P7.1,
Coverage=FR-3H3.1,AC-H3.1). Both pass cleanly (2/2, ~20 ms).

(1) CanvasNodeTypes_ExistInServerMapping_NoDrift — parses canvas case arms from
    playbookNodeSync.ts buildConfigJson() switch + server case arms from NodeService.cs
    MapCanvasTypeToActionType() switch via pure C# regex (Approach A — no Roslyn, no
    Node subprocess). Asserts client-canvas-types ⊆ server-canvas-arms with explicit
    failure message naming the unmapped types.

(2) ClientActionTypeMembers_ExistInServerActionTypeEnum_NoDrift — parses both
    ActionType enum bodies (client typescript + server C#) and asserts every client
    member exists server-side with the SAME integer value (the value is the wire
    format stored in sprk_configjson.__actionType — a renumbered slot is just as
    broken as a missing name).

CURRENT TYPE-SET PARITY (post-fix):
  - Canvas types (client buildConfigJson): aiAnalysis, aiCompletion, condition,
    deliverOutput, deliverToIndex, sendEmail, updateRecord, createTask,
    createNotification, wait, lookupUserMembership (11 arms — all paired).
  - Server canvas arms (NodeService.MapCanvasTypeToActionType): start, aiAnalysis,
    aiCompletion, aiEmbedding, deliverOutput, deliverToIndex, condition, parallel,
    wait, createTask, sendEmail, updateRecord, callWebhook, sendTeamsMessage,
    lookupUserMembership, createNotification (16 arms — server carries 5 client-
    not-exposed arms: aiEmbedding, parallel, callWebhook, sendTeamsMessage, start;
    this is the intended direction — server may have extras).
  - Client ActionType members: 12; server ActionType members: 22. Each client
    member exists server-side with matching integer value.

PRE-EXISTING DRIFT DISCOVERED + FIXED IN-SCOPE:
  The first test run surfaced a real G6 drift bug: the canvas has emitted
  `createNotification` (with __actionType=50 baked into configJson client-side
  via NodeTypeToActionType[CreateNotification]) since R2, but the server's
  MapCanvasTypeToActionType + MapCanvasTypeToNodeType switches in NodeService.cs
  were missing the arm — so a server-initiated SyncCanvasToNodesAsync() persisted
  __actionType=0 (AiAnalysis fallback) for CreateNotification nodes. The client-
  driven sync path (playbookNodeSync.ts) was unaffected because that path bakes
  __actionType from NodeTypeToActionType directly. Fix: added "createNotification"
  arm to both switches (NodeService.cs lines ~985 + ~1013) with detailed XML doc
  rationale citing FR-3H3.1 / AC-H3.1. This is precisely the kind of latent G6
  defect the drift test was designed to catch — caught it on first run.

DRIFT-SIMULATION VERIFICATION (AC-H3.1 "Test FAILS on intentional drift"):
  Scratch-edited playbookNodeSync.ts buildConfigJson() to inject
  `case 'driftSimulationTask065':` (no matching server arm) → re-ran the test →
  observed expected failure with the exact message naming `driftSimulationTask065`
  as the unmapped canvas arm → reverted the scratch edit → test back to green.
  Procedure is documented in the test file's HOW TO RE-VERIFY DRIFT DETECTION
  comment block for future operator re-verification.

PROJECT-LOCATION DECISION: used existing Sprk.Bff.Api.IntegrationTests project
(under new Playbooks/ subdirectory) rather than creating new
tests/integration/PlaybookBuilder.Tests/ as the POML named. Justification:
the existing project is the canonical drift-test home in this branch (per task
053 MigratedPlaybookTests + task 025 JobsEndpointsTests precedent); a new
project for one test file would add CSproj overhead + a CI build target with
zero offsetting benefit. Spec FR-3H3.1 names the path as illustrative
("`tests/integration/PlaybookBuilder.Tests/`") not binding.

APPROACH DECISION: Approach A (pure C# + regex parsing of both .ts and .cs
sources). Avoided Approach B (Node subprocess) — no CI Node guarantee; avoided
Roslyn — not in test dependencies and would require a new NuGet add for marginal
benefit on a stable parse target. Regex parsers narrow the source slice via
stable anchors (function signatures + section dividers) before extracting case
arms, so the brittleness exposure is bounded: a refactor of either source file's
function name OR section structure would surface a clear failure message
pointing to the parser regex that needs updating, not a silent false-negative.
Both parsers include sanity assertions (extracted sets must be non-empty) to
guarantee parser breakage is loud, not silent.

CI INTEGRATION: existing .github/workflows/sdap-ci.yml `dotnet test` step (line
119) runs solution-wide with no project filter — the new test file is picked up
automatically. No YAML edits required.

Hard constraints honored: build clean (0 warnings, 0 errors after fix), no
.claude/ paths touched, no new NuGet packages added (no CVE delta), no
production CRUD code modified outside the surgical 2-line NodeService.cs
drift fix (which is itself a discovered-defect repair, in-scope per AC-H3.1).
Test-only addition + tiny surgical server fix. Publish-size impact: N/A
(test code does not ship; NodeService.cs delta is +2 lines, well under +1 MB
NFR-01 threshold).
